To view VM details in KVM, you mainly use virsh. Here are the most useful commands (from quick summary → deep inspection):

✅ 1. Quick VM overview
virsh list --all
✅ 2. Full VM configuration (best command)
virsh dominfo alpine1
🔍 Output includes:
CPU(s)
Max memory
Used memory
State (running/shutoff)
✅ 3. Detailed configuration (XML)
virsh dumpxml alpine1

👉 This shows everything:

CPU config
Memory
Disk path
Network
Console
Boot order
✅ 4. Check CPU (vCPU details)
virsh vcpuinfo alpine1
✅ 5. Check memory
virsh dommemstat alpine1
✅ 6. Check disk details
virsh domblklist alpine1

Example output:

Target   Source
---------------------------------------------
vda      /var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine1.qcow2
More disk info:
virsh domblkinfo alpine1 vda
✅ 7. Check disk size (host side)
qemu-img info /var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine1.qcow2
✅ 8. Check network interfaces
virsh domiflist alpine1
✅ 9. Real-time usage (like top for VM)
virsh domstats alpine1
🚀 Most useful combo (practical)

If you want quick summary:

virsh dominfo alpine1
virsh domblklist alpine1
virsh domiflist alpine1
🧠 Example summary you’ll get
CPU: 2 vCPU
Memory: 1024 MB
Disk: /var/lib/libvirt/images/alpine1.qcow2
Network: virbr0 (default)
💡 Pro tip (very useful)

For quick readable output:

virsh dumpxml alpine1 | less
